			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1726">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>In her essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/364">They Always Call You &lsquo;Miss&rsquo;</a>&nbsp;&rdquo; [March 2005] Alison Clement perfectly describes the trials and tribulations of the waitressing experience &mdash; only they don&rsquo;t always call you &ldquo;miss.&rdquo; I wish they were so nice. Sometimes it&rsquo;s &ldquo;girlie&rdquo; or &ldquo;hey, you&rdquo; or &ldquo;babe&rdquo; or even &ldquo;foxy.&rdquo; (Is that a compliment?) Sometimes they don&rsquo;t call you anything; they just wave or snap their fingers.</p>

<p>There is something primal about food; it brings out the best and the worst in people. I know the satisfaction of giving people what they want even when they don&rsquo;t know what it is, and the rejection &mdash; not to mention the meager tip &mdash; when you get it wrong.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">C. Spivey<br>Dartmouth, Massachusetts</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1727">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Alison Clement&rsquo;s &ldquo;They Always Call You &lsquo;Miss&rsquo;&nbsp;&rdquo; was a kvetch piece of inordinate proportions. I don&rsquo;t know what circumstances brought Clement to waiting tables, but I hope she has some alternatives. She doesn&rsquo;t belong in a service job.</p>

<p>I have worked as a waiter myself and know it&rsquo;s hard work, but having such negative views of patrons only serves to make the work harder. I never looked down on the people I served, and I never looked down on myself for being in the position of serving others.</p>

<p>I have been a restaurant patron far longer than I was a waiter, and I could write a similar essay about waitpersons who are unprofessional in their approach, even rude or thoughtless, perhaps because they feel looked-down-upon by their customers. Respect is a two-way street.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Irwin Gooen<br>Oneonta, New York</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence-respond fill-pattern-light" id="1728">
								<p><a href="/contributors/alison-clement"><strong>Alison Clement</strong></a> responds:</p>
							<p>It&rsquo;s called humor, for crying out loud.</p>
	</div>


					</div>

